{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492988"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:52:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1198"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1198"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.01,0.25,0.19,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1198"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115842"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1198"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1198"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97846"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"3460"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3664"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19194"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49445"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115842"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with acute upper abdominal pain radiating to the back. This is his third presentation in four months with similar symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He previously consumed eight glasses of wine each weekend but has reduced his intake after medical advice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is tender in the epigastrium. Investigations reveal an alanine aminotransferase of 167 IU/L (5-40) and lipase 190 U/L (0-60). An ultrasound shows gallbladder stones.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Refer to drug and alcohol services","Encourage attendance at Alcoholics Anonymous","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography with sphincterotomy","Abdominal computed tomography scan","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with recurrent episodes of acute pancreatitis. While alcohol was initially suspected as the cause, ultrasound has now revealed gallstones, which are the most common cause of acute pancreatitis (35-75% of cases).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive treatment for biliary pancreatitis and should be performed during the index admission for mild cases. This reduces the risk of recurrence to almost zero. The procedure involves removing the gallbladder after isolating and dividing the cystic duct and artery. Even if the patient also has a history of consuming alcohol (many do) this should still be performed with patients with pancreatitis and evidence of gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal computed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E scanning is only indicated if there is diagnostic uncertainty or if pancreatic enzyme levels are normal. Early CT scanning has not been shown to improve outcomes and may prolong hospital stay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E with sphincterotomy is only indicated in biliary pancreatitis when there is concurrent cholangitis or common bile duct obstruction. This patient shows no evidence of these complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to drug and alcohol services\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eattendance at Alcoholics Anonymous\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful supportive measures, but addressing the underlying gallstone disease is the priority to prevent further episodes of pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring cholecystectomy, an operative cholangiogram will be performed to identify any common bile duct stones that may require removal at the same time.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Laparoscopic cholecystectomy during index admission is recommended for mild biliary pancreatitis to prevent recurrence.","Gallstones are the most common cause of acute pancreatitis (35-75% of cases).","Early ERCP is only indicated in biliary pancreatitis with concurrent cholangitis or common bile duct obstruction."],"references":["James TW, Crockett SD. Management of Acute Pancreatitis in the First 72 hours. Curr Opin Gastroenterol. 2018; 34: 330\u201333. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29957661/","Nesvaderani M, Eslick G, Cox M. Acute pancreatitis: update on management. Medical Journal of Australia. 2015;202(8):420-423. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2015/202/8/acute-pancreatitis-update-management","Trust M, Sheffield K, Boyd C, Benarroch-Gampel J, Zhang D, Townsend C et al. Gallstone pancreatitis in older patients: Are we operating enough?. Surgery. 2011;150(3):515-525. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3353416/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97846"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1198"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97846"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-25T17:03:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T17:04:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1198"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115842"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at